    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-08-24T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-08-24T11:00:00-05:00" n="455"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">862.60/8–2447: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_DLW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Douglas</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">urgent</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-08-24T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 24, 1947—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4587. For <persName corresp="#p_LRA1">Lovett</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_DLW1">Douglas</persName>. Last night <persName corresp="#p_JSG1"
                        >Sir Gilmour Jenkins</persName>, two or three of the British delegates;
                        <persName corresp="#p_MR1">Massigli</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_AH1"
                        >Alphand</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SR1">Sergent</persName>
                    <pb facs="1093" n="1059" xml:id="pg_1059"/> for the French; <persName
                        corresp="#p_MR3">Murphy</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CLD1"
                        >Clay</persName> and I dined together. It was my impression that after the
                    formal discussions today, we can subsequently reach an agreement on a
                    satisfactory communiqué which will give the French Government at least a public
                    statement which they can in turn use to persuade French public opinion.</p>
                <p>While neither <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> nor <persName
                        corresp="#p_MR1">Massigli</persName> have as yet either formally or
                    informally explicitly referred to an allocating board, the proposal is implicit
                    in what <persName corresp="#p_AH1">Alphand</persName> said on Friday. It may
                    well be that in preparing the communiqué, we may be able to negotiate a
                    satisfactory language if I know that it can include something along the
                    following lines: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“US Govt at the appropriate time and the appropriate place will view with
                            sympathetic consideration and engage in discussions on the subject of
                            establishment of an allocating board or some other device for the
                            purpose of ensuring that access to products of the Ruhr shall not in
                            future as was the case in the prewar period be exclusively subject to
                            the will of Germany.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>If you can see your way clear to defining “appropriate time and place” as
                    immediately or shortly following the termination of these discussions, it would
                    be extremely helpful, it being understood always that such an allocating board
                    would not come into existence until after the peace settlement had become
                    effective.</p>
                <p>Please give us a prompt answer as the matter may be coming to a head today or
                        tomorrow.<note n="16" xml:id="d455fn1">
                        <p>Telegram 3663, August 24, to London, from <persName corresp="#p_LRA1"
                                >Lovett</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_DLW1"
                            >Douglas</persName>, not printed, gave the following interim reply:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“There is considerable difference of views here re subject your
                                    4587 which may have to be resolved at highest level. If after
                                    your discussing matter with <persName corresp="#p_CLD1"
                                        >Clay</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_MR3"
                                        >Murphy</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CLD1"
                                        >Clay</persName> could recommend your suggestion to <gloss
                                        target="#t_War1">War</gloss> matter would be simpler here
                                    and earlier solution probable.” (862.60/8–2447)</p>
                            </quote>
                        </p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Department 4587; repeated Paris for <persName corresp="#p_CJ1"
                        >Caffery</persName> 476; Berlin for <persName corresp="#p_MR3"
                        >Murphy</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CLD1">Clay</persName> 398;
                    Geneva for <persName corresp="#p_CWL1">Clayton</persName> 127.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DLW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Douglas</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
